{{Refimprove|date=April 2014}}
'''Fugitive pigments''' are [[wikt:impermanent|impermanent]] [[pigment]]s that lighten, darken, or otherwise change in appearance or physicality over time when exposed to certain environmental conditions, such as light, temperature, humidity, or pollution.<ref>{{cite book|last=Field|first=George|title=Field's Chromatography or Treatise on Colours and Pigments as Used by Artists|year=1869|publisher=Project Guttenberg|location=London|page=31|url=http://www.gutenberg.org|edition=Salter's|editor=Thomas W. Salter|accessdate=March 9, 2014|archivedate=March 27, 2007|chapter=4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Looking at Paintings: A Guide to Technical Terms|year=2009|publisher=J. Paul Getty Museum|location=Los Angeles|page=59|url=http://www.getty.edu|author=Tiarna Doherty|edition=Revised|author2=Anne T. Woollett}}</ref>  Fugitive pigments are present in types of [[paint]], [[Marker pen|marker]]s, [[ink]]s etc., which are used for temporary applications. Fugitive inks which washed away when soaked in water were sometimes used deliberately to prevent [[postage stamp]]s being removed from envelopes by soaking, and reused (e.g., the [[Queen Victoria Lilac and Green Issue]]).

While permanent pigments are usually used for [[painting]]s, painters have made work wholly or partially with fugitive pigments for a number of reasons: availability and cost of pigments; being more concerned with the appearance of colors available only with fugitive pigments than with permanence; ignorance regarding the volatility of the pigments; or the desire to have a painting change in appearance over time.

