The '''''Madonna on a Crescent Moon in'' Hortus{{nbsp}}Conclusus''' is a 1450s painting by an unknown artist referred to as the “{{nowrap|Master of 1456}}”.<ref name="Larson2013">{{citation |mode=cs1 |last=Larson |first=Victoria |title=A Rose Blooms in the Winter: The Tradition of the ''Hortus&nbsp;Conclusus'' and its Significance as a Devotional Emblem |journal=Dialog |publisher=Wiley–Blackwell |volume=52 |issue=4 |year=2013 |pages=303–312 |doi=10.1111/dial.12066 |issn=0012-2033 |oclc=5497226523 |subscription=yes}}</ref>{{rp|309,{{nbsp}}312}}<ref name="WGA">{{citation|mode=cs1 |title=Madonna on a Crescent Moon in ''Hortus&nbsp;Conclusus'' by Unknown Master, German |publisher=Web Gallery of Art |url=http://www.wga.hu/html/m/master/zunk_ge/zunk_ge2/10madonn.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123210639/http://www.wga.hu/html/m/master/zunk_ge/zunk_ge2/10madonn.html |archive-date=23 November 2015 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref> It is held by the [[Gemäldegalerie]] in [[Berlin]].

[[Hortus Conclusus]] is Latin for “enclosed garden”, a [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] of biblical origin where the [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Virgin{{nbsp}}Mary]] herself is represented as a garden.<ref name="Larson2013"/>{{rp|303}}{{Clear}}

